An '''RDP shop''' is a website where access to [[Zombie (computer science)|hacked computers]] is sold to [[Cybercrime|cybercriminals]].

The computers may be acquired via scanning the web for open [[Remote Desktop Protocol]] connections and [[Brute-force attack|brute-forcing]] passwords.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Olenick |first1=Doug |title=Dark Web shops selling RDP connections on the cheap |url=https://www.scmagazine.com/dark-web-shops-selling-rdp-connections-on-the-cheap/article/780065/ |accessdate=27 August 2018 |date=11 July 2018}}</ref> High-value [[ransomware]] targets are sometimes available such as airports.<ref>{{cite news |last1=International Airport Review |title=Hackers can buy access to a major airport’s security systems for just $10 |url=https://www.internationalairportreview.com/news/72390/hackers-airports-security-systems/ |accessdate=27 August 2018 |date=17 July 2018}}</ref> Access to a compromised machine retails from $3 to $19 depending on automatically gathered system and network metrics using a standardised [[Backdoor (computing)|back door]].<ref name="ddw" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=THE ASIAN AGE |title=Organisations vulnerable to cheap RDP attacks: Report |url=http://www.asianage.com/technology/in-other-news/160718/organisations-vulnerable-to-cheap-rdp-attacks-report.html |accessdate=27 August 2018 |date=16 Jul 2018}}</ref>

Russian sites such as [[xDedic]]<ref name="ddw">{{cite news|last1=Guerrilla|first1=American|title=xDedic is Back in Business on the Dark Web|url=https://www.deepdotweb.com/2016/07/19/xdedic-back-business-dark-web/|accessdate=22 December 2016|date=19 July 2016}}</ref> do not sell access to machines within the [[Commonwealth of Independent States|former Soviet nations]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=SCUK |title=Russian underground shop selling RDP servers for £11 or less |url=https://www.scmagazineuk.com/russian-underground-shop-selling-rdp-servers-11-less/article/1473917 |accessdate=27 August 2018 |date=25 October 2017}}</ref>

